context: From Elizabeth's birth onwards, the British Empire continued its transformation into the <a0_0>Commonwealth of Nations<a0_0/>. By the time of her accession in <a1_0><b5_0>1952<b5_0/><a1_0/>, her role as head of multiple independent states was already established. In 1953, the Queen and her husband embarked on a seven-month <a2_0>round-the-world tour<a2_0/>, visiting <a3_0>13 countries<a3_0/> and covering more than <a4_0><b8_0><b9_0>40,000<b9_0/><b8_0/> miles<a4_0/> by land, sea and air. She became the first reigning monarch of <b6_0>Australia<b6_0/> and <b7_0>New Zealand<b7_0/> to visit those nations. During the tour, crowds were immense; three-quarters of the population of Australia were estimated to have seen her. Throughout her reign, the Queen has made hundreds of state visits to other countries and tours of the Commonwealth; she is the most widely travelled head of state.
